{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T18:01:06.152457+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T18:01:06.706441+00:00", "id": 19667926, "conceptrecid": "19667925", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19667926", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19667925", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19667926", "metadata": {"title": "Infectious Diseases Associated with Caves", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19667926", "publication_date": "2011", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) In recent times, caving has become increasingly popular, with almost 2 million people visiting national park caves each year in the United States. Although the 2 million tourist visits are extremely low risk, smaller numbers of sport cavers are at risk for some high risk conditions, and expedition cavers are at risk for some obscure infections. Infectious diseases like histoplasmosis, rabies, leptospirosis, and tick-borne relapsing fever may be transmitted by the underground fauna. To reduce the risk of illness or injury while caving, knowledge of potential risks before engaging in this activity is important. Caving preparation needs to be carefully planned and executed, including vaccinations, prophylactic medications, and advice regarding safe conduct and behaviors.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Igreja, Ricardo Pereira", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/bb458a1012e510f27a9e9a5daef44e83", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/e68e3fb960402a754a647f3d3c1c4bf8130b7286928ac9a39d315a25432f50a2", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/IC82PQQ9", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/IC82PQQ9", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:has